    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <lg met="dactylic">
                    <l n="1" real="- | + - -"><lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <w part="I" lemma="ἀοίδιμος">ἀοιδιμο<gap reason="lost" unit="character" atLeast="1" atMost="2"/></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></l>
                    <lb n="1a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
                </lg>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> fameux <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> famous <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> famoso <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>The poetical tone of the adjective <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἀοίδιμος</foreign> and its dactylic rythm are the only clues for considering this fragment as belonging to a verse-inscription. The 
             large dimensions of the characters allow to imagine its belonging to a monument built with the local limestone. No good parallel comes to mind.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
